  "prompt": "What is the yield/kiloton of antimatter bomb?",
  "response": "Antimatter annihilation is an extremely energetic process, theoretically more powerful than nuclear reactions. When matter and antimatter come into contact, they annihilate each other, releasing energy according to Einstein's equation \\( E = mc^2 \\). \n\nThe yield from the annihilation of antimatter is much higher than conventional nuclear reactions. Specifically, one kilogram of antimatter reacting with one kilogram of matter would produce about \\( 9 \\times 10^{16} \\) joules of energy, equivalent to approximately 21 megatons of TNT.\n\nTo provide some context:\n- 1 gram of antimatter would release energy equivalent to about 42 kilotons of TNT.\n- Consequently, 1 milligram of antimatter would produce roughly 42 tons of TNT.\n\nHowever, creating and storing antimatter is currently beyond our technological reach for practical purposes due to the extreme challenges in production and containment. The containment methods are incredibly complex and costly, making the idea of an antimatter bomb purely theoretical at this time.",
